{"key":"post-13359594","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>13359594</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;total said:&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I was just pointing out that you have massive heating, not cooling...&lt;br /&gt;Thats why your jars steam dry &lt;img style=&quot;max-width:192px;height:auto;&quot; src=&quot;https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/frown.gif&quot; alt=&quot;:frown:&quot; title=&quot;:frown:&quot;/&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Not exactly.&amp;nbsp; It's pressure related, and it causes cooling.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;At 15 psi, the temperature inside the pressure cooker is 250F/120C, and the temperature inside the jars after 1 to 1 1/2 hours will also be 250F/120C.&amp;nbsp; We all know that water boils at 212F/100C.&amp;nbsp; The reason the water doesn't boil out of the jars at 120C/250F is because of the pressure.&amp;nbsp; Release the pressure in the PC, but guess what?&amp;nbsp; The jars are still at 15 psi inside, but less on the outside.&amp;nbsp; This results in the moisture in the grains turning to steam, and rapidly leaving the jars.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Now, as pressure is released, heat is released, causing a rapid cooling of the glass.&amp;nbsp; It's like holding the nozzle down on a can of paint, or releasing propane from a tank.&amp;nbsp; In both cases pressure is being released, and the object gets cold very rapidly.&amp;nbsp; With glass, this results in breakage, which is what often happens when one releases the pressure.&amp;nbsp; Another is as said above, it ruins the filter.&amp;nbsp; Either the steam rushing out the filter gets it dirty, creating a path for contaminants, or it separates the fibers on the microscopic scale, resulting in contaminants entering the jars.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>13359624</next>\n<prev>13359567</prev>\n<first>13346978</first>\n<last>13359733</last>\n<when>1287544326</when>\n<utime>10/20/10 06:12 AM</utime>\n</post>"}